<TITLE> Bomb wounds 15 soldiers in Muslim Thai south </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BANGKOK, Dec 12 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A roadside bomb wounded 15 soldiers, four of them seriously, in Thailand's rebellious Muslim south on Wednesday, police said. The bomb badly damaged a military bus ferrying soldiers to Pattani, one of three southernmost provinces where more than 2,600 people have been killed in a nearly four-year-old separatist insurgency. "It looks like the culprits tried to retaliate against our current military efforts to corner them. They might also want to create trouble before the election" on Dec. 23, said an army officer in Pattani who declined to be identified. There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the blast and there was unlikely to be one. The organisation of the militants in the former sultanate annexed by predominately Buddhist Thailand a century ago remains murky and nobody claims responsiblity for the near daily gun and bomb attacks. Since July, security forces in the Malay-speaking region have in turn launched almost daily raids on suspected insurgent hideouts and detained dozens of people without charge. Human rights groups say detainees are exposed to potential abuses by the army, operating under martial law that grants soldiers immunity from prosecuti
